The brand new bullpup-rifle from IWI that's taking the world of modern semi-auto rifles by storm. After more than a decade of collaboration and testing with the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) - the TAVOR® rifle was born. Just as race car technology trickles down to consumer automobiles, so do these time and battle-tested firearms now become a modern sporting rifle platform for civilian gun enthusiasts.

The TAVOR® is a perfect fusion of an ordnance grade steel receiver coupled to a Mil-Spec cold hammer forged barrel and encased into a high-impact strength polymer uni-body with exceptional situational ergonomics. The ultra-compact form factor allows for easy transitions in close quarter situations…or even in your favorite deer blind. The bullpup design moves the center of gravity of the rifle closer to the users’ body allowing for more instinctive aiming and improved acquisition time to target. This innovative design also allows for a full length barrel, which means no loss of down range ballistic accuracy. Near and far range accuracy is enhanced by the minimized recoil provided by a non-lubricated long stroke gas piston system. With the exception of a hand-specific locking bolt, the rifle is completely ambidextrous allowing for easy left-hand conversion of the operating handle, ejection port, fire-control safety, sling swivel receptacles and fore-mounted accessory Picatinny rail. The TAVOR® is supplied with IDF-tested and approved magazines – but you can also use your own AR-15/M16 style magazines.

title: For Sale:  Swedish m40 Lahti 9mm Military Pistol
postcontent:
Swedish Lahti m40 9mm Pistol. Stock # MMH282003. Serial # 429xx. This is a 9MM Swedish Model m40 9mm semi-auto pistol, sometimes referred to as a “Lahti” Pistol. Made in Sweden by Husqvarna, this was the standard Swedish Military sidearm from the 1940’s to Post-WWII. The Lahti is a unique semi-auto pistol, in that the trigger has an accellerator in it that allows the pistol to be fired in sub-zero conditions. The pistol has a blue factory finish and brown plastic checkered factory grips with the Hsqvarna logo. There are faint importers markings on the right front of the receiver, the Husqvarna markings are crisp and legible. The magazine is not marked. The pistol has heavy holster wear, wear on the grip straps, service marks, and there is a large spot of discoloration on top of the slide. The grips show minimal wear. The brand new bullpup-rifle from IWI that's taking the world of modern semi-auto rifles by storm. After more than a decade of collaboration and testing with the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) - the TAVOR® rifle was born. Just as race car technology trickles down to consumer automobiles, so do these time and battle-tested firearms now become a modern sporting rifle platform for civilian gun enthusiasts.

The TAVOR® is a perfect fusion of an ordnance grade steel receiver coupled to a Mil-Spec cold hammer forged barrel and encased into a high-impact strength polymer uni-body with exceptional situational ergonomics. The ultra-compact form factor allows for easy transitions in close quarter situations…or even in your favorite deer blind. The bullpup design moves the center of gravity of the rifle closer to the users’ body allowing for more instinctive aiming and improved acquisition time to target. This innovative design also allows for a full length barrel, which means no loss of down range ballistic accuracy. Near and far range accuracy is enhanced by the minimized recoil provided by a non-lubricated long stroke gas piston system. With the exception of a hand-specific locking bolt, the rifle is completely ambidextrous allowing for easy left-hand conversion of the operating handle, ejection port, fire-control safety, sling swivel receptacles and fore-mounted accessory Picatinny rail. The TAVOR® is supplied with IDF-tested and approved magazines – but you can also use your own AR-15/M16 style magazines.

title: For Sale:  AR500 Steel Rifle & Pistol Targets
postcontent:
1/2" Thick AR500 Steel Targets suitable for Rifle & Pistol practice.

Sizes Available:
  $95 - Med Silhouette (Overall: 12"W x 16"H Neck: 4"W x 6"H)
  $50 - Small Silhouette (Overall: 8"W x 12"H Neck: 3"W x 4"H)
  $30 - Bowler (4"W x 12"H)
  $10 - Can (2.5"W x 4"H)

These are better prices than the 3/8" thick target you will normally 
find at the gun shows or online.  You can save a lot of money painting 
them yourself and by purchasing you own hardware to hang.  If you are 
looking to get 5+ targets let me know, if requested quantity is still 
available I might be able to offer a package price.

Targets are ready to hang with 1/2" carriage bolts (grade 5 
recommended).

Email or text is the best way to reach me.  Thanks for looking.

Basic guidelines:
1. Always wear eye protection/safety glasses.
2. Never shoot at the flat face of a steel target, recommended tilt 
angle is 20 - 30 degrees so the bullet is directed toward the ground and
 not up or back towards the firing line.
3. Maintain a safe distance: 10+ yards for pistol calibers & 25 - 
100 yards for rifle calibers.  The more powerful the more distance 
required for safety.
4. Hang targets (still at an angle) with chain, rubber or nylon belting 
(versus rigid mount to a board) to allow targets to dissipate more of 
the bullets energy and direct more of the splatter to the ground.  There
 are a lot of examples online of safe and inexpensive to build target 
hangers.  This will also improve the sound of the "ring" when you hit 
the target.

Notice:  You are responsible for the safe and proper use of these 
targets.  If you have not shot at steel targets or do not understand the
 risks and hazards of ricochets and bullet splatter, please ask someone 
for guidance and/or investigate online before firing your first shot at 
steel.

title: For Sale:  Dissipator AR-15 - price drop
postcontent:
This is a Palmetto state armory upper on a Rock River lower. The barrel is 16", with a mid-length gas system and rifle length sight radius/handguards. Bolt and carrier are all mil-spec. Chrome-lined bore, chambered in 5.56 so will handle .223 as well. The mid-length gas system makes for really soft shooting and the rifle-length sight radius gives a much better sight picture than carbine length.

The stock is a B5 systems SOPMOD stock with battery storage and includes a quick detach sling swivel. The handguard is a Midwest Industries Gen 2 quad rail - a really nice, lightweight rail. The rail covers are Larue Tactical Index Clips, which are great - each one takes up a single slot so you can use them to mark where your optic mount goes if you need to remove it. Easily the lowest profile rail covers I've used. The grip on it right now is a standard M4/M16 style grip. The rear backup iron sight is a Magpul MBUS Pro - all-steel construction and lies perfectly flat at the very rear of your rifle. Don't notice it until you need it. Includes the vertical foregrip pictured. Includes two GI magazines.

This is a really great shooting AR and I wish I didn't have to sell it off. It's accurate and reliable, I've never had any issues at all with it. It hasn't gone on any carbine courses or anything that would constitute as hard use - just to the range and back. It hasn't reached the 1000rd mark yet, so it has tons of life left in it.

Looking for $700 but open to offers.

title: For Sale:  ATI 1911
postcontent:
http://www.budsgunshop.com/catalog/product_info.php/cPath/21_859/products_id/75562/ATI+Firepower+Xtreme%3A+Military+1911

-OR-  

http://www.gunbroker.com/All/BI.aspx?Keywords=ATIGFX45MIL

BNIB, as usual, with warranty and receipt. 

Thats a $350 gun on the second hand market, all day, and thats being generous.

Taxes and fees are what people pay when they buy a gun at an FFL, who will issue you a receipt for returns and the gun usually is also backed by a factory warranty. 
Otherwise, your taking your chances with someone else's gun and the thin guarantee of the sellers word. 
Unless the manufacturer honors warranties when the piece is sold second hand, which most do not, the new owner of your gun must pay out of pocket if it needs repair.

Your prices should reflect this.

Thats sort of the risk we all take when we buy a second hand gun on the second hand market, your prices should reflect that, and thats what makes this market unique and worthwhile- people can find deals here, but with the prices I'm seeing some of you asking, we might as well go to the nearest FFL. (and we'd STILL likely pay less, even AFTER the taxes lol).

I don't think alot of folks here seem to understand this.

Its like a car, the moment you drive it off the lot, its USED, and selling it after that does not command retail prices, let alone even MORE then retail. 

All this "its like new in box I never fired it once I swear" or "its only had 20 rounds down range I promise" is NOT a substitute for a receipt and factory warranty.

If you really wanna sell your gun offer people a reasonable deal, and that means you need to START at the used price end, not what you paid or what it goes for BNIB.

Is there any wonder why some listings just languish on the list for months on end?

title: For Sale:  Rossi .243 Single Shot Rifle model R243YBS NIB Scope Mount Hammer Spur Lever Safety Internal Lock Swivels Detachable Monte Carlo 13 1/4 inch Pull
postcontent: OUR # LGR243YBSHere is the last of a classic little rifle, the Rossi R243 in black synthetic with scope mount and fiber optic sights. Manufacturer is Taurus Held Amadeo Rossi S.A. of Sao Leopoldo, Brazil. Importer and warrantor is Braztech of Miami. Type is breech lever single shot center fire rifle. Chambering is .243 Winchester caliber. Rossi lists it as a youth rifle, but its length and proportions are adult sized. Metal is entirely blue steel, with polymer trigger guard. Stock and forend are graphite based black synthetic. Barrel is 22 inch medium tapered, .635 outside diameter at the muzzle, .700 osd at the forend tip, and 1.105 at the breech face. Bore is six groove button rifled 1:10 right hand. Sights are screw on polymer, high ramp type front with red fiber optic insert, and 700 type rear with dual green fiber optic insert, and that is windage and elevation adjustable. Scope base is Weaver number 92A, 4 slot with 4 screw retention. Trigger is .312 smooth faced steel, with .300 serrated spur hammer. Breech lever is on the right side of the hammer. Trigger pulls at 4 pounds vicinity, with negligible felt creep. Receiver has a transfer bar safety device, a receiver mounted lever safety, and an internal hammer lock. Chamber has an extractor, not an ejector. Forend is short schnabel type with lateral checkring, and buttstock has a detachable Monte Carlo that will raise the comb drop from 1 1/2 inches installed to 2 inches removed. Buttstock length of pull is 13 1/4 inches from the trigger face to the end of the 3/4 inch recoil pad. Forend and buttstock have blued steel sling swivels. Buttstock has a 3/4 inch right hand cant, so this rifle is not altogether southpaw friendly. Weight empty is 6 pounds 9.5 ounces, with center of gravity at the receiver’s pivot pin. Overall length is a relatively compact 36 1/2 inches. Each R243 comes in its factory box with protective papers, instruction manual, safety flyers, two keys for its hammer lock, and factory registration card. Its size is about the same as competitor H&R, but a pound lighter. From our local shooters’ experience, the Rossi outshoots the H&R. Dealer cost on H&R Handi Rifles is $200 or more. title: For Sale:  Russian TT33 WWII Tokarev GI Bring Back +Holster
location: South Dakota, South Dakota, United States
postcontent:
Russian T33 WWII Tokarev G.I. Bringback w/Holster
The popular pistol & sub-machine gun caliber of the Russian Army in WWII was the bottle-neck 7.62x25mm cartridge known here as the .30 Tokarev. This pistol & proper issue holster is a genuine American G.I. War souvenir with no import marks.

Overall condition is Good to Good+. A “gray gun” with some original blue in protected areas. Matching #'s on frame, slide, barrel, hammer/sear assy. 4 ½” barrel has strong rifling w/medium pitting from corrosive WWII ammo. Original “CCCP” marked grips w/Russian-Commie star...no cracks/chips, just normal wear/dings from combat use.

Comes with an original WWII Russian issue brown leather holster (see “Military Holsters of WWII” by Bender, p. 179) in fair condition, showing several field repairs to the belt straps.

The lanyard loop mag, w/Russian star, is in very good condition. It is from the “YH” series, so it was produced a little after this “YA” series pistol, but is still late war correct.
